<Hops><_MOD_>2014-08-05</_MOD_>
<F_H_NAME>Southern Passion 2013</F_H_NAME>
<F_H_ORIGIN>South Africa</F_H_ORIGIN>
<F_H_TYPE>1</F_H_TYPE>
<F_H_FORM>0</F_H_FORM>
<F_H_ALPHA>11.0000000</F_H_ALPHA>
<F_H_BETA>7.5000000</F_H_BETA>
<F_H_PERCENT>7.6923062</F_H_PERCENT>
<F_H_INVENTORY>15.8732830</F_H_INVENTORY>
<F_H_AMOUNT>0.5291094</F_H_AMOUNT>
<F_H_HSI>5.0000000</F_H_HSI>
<F_H_BOIL_TIME>60.0000000</F_H_BOIL_TIME>
<F_H_DRY_HOP_TIME>0.0000000</F_H_DRY_HOP_TIME>
<F_H_NOTES>Fruity, passion fruit and slightly spicy.

Formerly known as US4/78. This locally bred aroma type hop variety was selected specifically for South African conditions.  It is a very vigorous variety requiring wide planting distances.  The medium size cones are slightly spiky, neat and tight with an average cone weight of 0.16g.  The cone to leaf ratio is 80:20.

Cohumulone 16.6-20.2%, Total Oil ml/100g 0.8-1.0%, Humulene 17-26%, Caryophyllene 10-13%, Hum/Car Ratio 2.7 &ndash; 3.4%, Farnesene 0.1-0.4%, Myrcene 20-35%
</F_H_NOTES>
<F_H_IBU_CONTRIB>19.3778195</F_H_IBU_CONTRIB>
<F_ORDER>6</F_ORDER>
<F_H_USE>0</F_H_USE>
<F_H_IN_RECIPE>1</F_H_IN_RECIPE>
<F_H_PRICE>2.8349523</F_H_PRICE>
</Hops>
<Hops><_MOD_>1970-02-01</_MOD_>
<F_H_NAME>J17/63 2013</F_H_NAME>
<F_H_ORIGIN>South Africa</F_H_ORIGIN>
<F_H_TYPE>2</F_H_TYPE>
<F_H_FORM>0</F_H_FORM>
<F_H_ALPHA>12.0000000</F_H_ALPHA>
<F_H_BETA>4.5000000</F_H_BETA>
<F_H_PERCENT>15.3846241</F_H_PERCENT>
<F_H_INVENTORY>10.0530791</F_H_INVENTORY>
<F_H_AMOUNT>1.0582196</F_H_AMOUNT>
<F_H_HSI>15.0000000</F_H_HSI>
<F_H_BOIL_TIME>15.0000000</F_H_BOIL_TIME>
<F_H_DRY_HOP_TIME>0.0000000</F_H_DRY_HOP_TIME>
<F_H_NOTES>Gooseberries, Cassis, Chilli, Gazpacho.

Experimental SAB hop. J17/63 is a day neutral high alpha variety, which requires moderate planting distances and an average of 9-10000 strings and 27-30000 bines per hectare.  Bines are vigorous and perform well on a standard framework. The medium sized cones with an average weight of 0.24g are semi tight, dense and pick very easily.  The cone to leaf ratio is 60:40.  Alpha development is normal.

Because of the excellent alpha acids content and good yields, J17/63 gives a very high alpha acid production per hectare.

Cohumulone 26.5%, Storeability (Pellets) TBC, Isomerisation (Pellets) TBC, Total Oil ml/100g 1.3%, Humulene 21.4%, Caryophyllene 12.8%, Hum/Car Ratio 1.7, Farnesene 4.9, Myrcene 28.4%</F_H_NOTES>
<F_H_IBU_CONTRIB>11.2743762</F_H_IBU_CONTRIB>
<F_ORDER>7</F_ORDER>
<F_H_USE>0</F_H_USE>
<F_H_IN_RECIPE>1</F_H_IN_RECIPE>
<F_H_PRICE>2.8349523</F_H_PRICE>
</Hops>
